## Summary

I've thoroughly explored the Prisma codebase to understand DMMF (Data Model Meta Format) structure and how existing generators use it to produce code. Here's my comprehensive report:

---

## DMMF Structure

### Core DMMF Document (`packages/dmmf/src/dmmf.ts`)

The DMMF is a complete schema representation with three main sections:

```typescript
export type Document = {
  datamodel: Datamodel      // The data model (models, enums, types)
  schema: Schema            // The GraphQL-like schema for API operations
  mappings: Mappings        // Model operation mappings
}
```

### Datamodel Structure

```typescript
export type Datamodel = {
  models: Model[]           // Database models (tables)
  enums: DatamodelEnum[]    // Enum definitions
  types: Model[]            // Composite types
  indexes: Index[]          // Index definitions
}
```

### Model Definition

```typescript
export type Model = {
  name: string
  dbName: string | null     // Database name if different
  schema: string | null     // Database schema
  fields: Field[]           // Model fields
  uniqueFields: string[][]
  uniqueIndexes: uniqueIndex[]
  documentation?: string
  primaryKey: PrimaryKey | null
  isGenerated?: boolean
}
```

### Field Structure (The Most Important)

```typescript
export type FieldKind = 'scalar' | 'object' | 'enum' | 'unsupported'

export type Field = {
  kind: FieldKind           // Type of field
  name: string
  isRequired: boolean
  isList: boolean           // Is array type []
  isUnique: boolean
  isId: boolean             // Primary key
  isReadOnly: boolean
  isGenerated?: boolean
  isUpdatedAt?: boolean
  type: string              // e.g., "String", "Int", "BigInt", "User" (model ref)
  nativeType?: [string, string[]] | null  // e.g., ['VarChar', ['191']]
  dbName?: string | null
  hasDefaultValue: boolean
  default?: FieldDefault | FieldDefaultScalar | FieldDefaultScalar[]

  // Relation fields
  relationFromFields?: string[]  // Local FK fields
  relationToFields?: string[]    // Remote PK fields
  relationOnDelete?: string      // CASCADE, SET_NULL, etc.
  relationOnUpdate?: string
  relationName?: string          // @relation name
  documentation?: string
}
```

---

## Generator Architecture

### Entry Point: `GeneratorOptions`
(`packages/generator/src/configuration.ts`)

Generators receive options containing:

```typescript
export type GeneratorOptions = {
  generator: GeneratorConfig        // Generator configuration
  dmmf: DMMF.Document              // The complete DMMF document
  schemaPath: string               // Path to schema.prisma file
  datamodel: string                // Raw schema.prisma content
  datasources: DataSource[]        // Database connections
  version: string                  // Engine version hash
  binaryPaths?: BinaryPaths        // Path to engine binaries
  typedSql?: SqlQueryOutput[]      // Typed SQL queries if enabled
}
```

### Generator Handler Implementation
(`packages/generator-helper/src/generatorHandler.ts`)

Generators implement a simple interface:

```typescript
export interface Handler {
  onGenerate(options: GeneratorOptions): Promise<any>
  onManifest?(config: GeneratorConfig): GeneratorManifest | Promise<GeneratorManifest>
}

// Called via JSON-RPC from the Prisma CLI
export function generatorHandler(handler: Handler): void {
  // Reads JSON-RPC messages from stdin
  // Calls handler.onGenerate() when 'generate' method is invoked
  // Writes responses to stderr
}
```

---

## Real-World Generator Usage: Prisma Client JS

### Step 1: Entry Point (`packages/client-generator-js/src/generator.ts`)

```typescript
export class PrismaClientJsGenerator implements Generator {
  async generate(options: GeneratorOptions): Promise<void> {
    const outputDir = parseEnvValue(options.generator.output!)

    await generateClient({
      dmmf: options.dmmf,           // Pass DMMF to generator
      datamodel: options.datamodel,
      schemaPath: options.schemaPath,
      outputDir,
      generator: options.generator,
      // ... more options
    })
  }
}
```

### Step 2: Build Client (`packages/client-generator-js/src/generateClient.ts`)

Creates in-memory representation of files as a `FileMap` object:

```typescript
export interface FileMap {
  [name: string]: string | FileMap  // Files or subdirectories
}

// Generate code using TSClient class
const nodeClient = new TSClient(nodeClientOptions)

const fileMap: FileMap = {
  'index.js': JS(nodeClient),           // JavaScript output
  'index.d.ts': TS(nodeClient),         // TypeScript definitions
  'default.js': JS(defaultClient),
  'package.json': JSON.stringify(pkgJson),
  'schema.prisma': datamodel,
}

// Write all files to disk
await writeFileMap(outputDir, fileMap)
```

### Step 3: Iterate Over Models (`packages/client-generator-js/src/TSClient/TSClient.ts`)

```typescript
public toTS(): string {
  // Create a Model generator for each model/type in DMMF
  const modelAndTypes = Object.values(this.dmmf.typeAndModelMap).reduce((acc, modelOrType) => {
    if (this.dmmf.outputTypeMap.model[modelOrType.name]) {
      acc.push(new Model(modelOrType, context))  // Create Model generator
    }
    return acc
  }, [] as Model[])

  // Generate code for each model
  const code = `
    ${modelAndTypes.map((m) => m.toTSWithoutNamespace()).join('\n')}
  `
